{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478738"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:15:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:15:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18523"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18523"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0,0.2,0.66,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11252"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104523"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11252"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18523"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86850"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"7908"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37469"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104523"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with a three-month history of painful, cracked skin on the soles of his feet. The condition worsens after physical activity. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. He has a family history of his mother having psoriasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The anterior plantar surface of both feet shows smooth, shiny, erythematous patches with several painful fissures more so on the plantar aspect of the great toes. The heels and toe webs are spared. There is no scaling, vesicles, or pustules. His parent mentions he plays soccer three times per week.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wet dressings","Oral antihistamines","Topical antifungal cream","Regular emollient and barrier cream","Topical corticosteroid cream"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical features of juvenile plantar dermatosis (JPD) (winter feet or forefoot dermatitis), a condition characterised by smooth, shiny, red skin on the forefoot with painful fissuring. It commonly affects children aged 3-14 years and is associated with occlusive footwear and increased physical activity causing friction on the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular emollient and barrier cream\u003C/strong\u003E application is the mainstay of treatment for JPD. This helps to protect the skin barrier and prevent moisture loss. The use of barrier creams (such as zinc oxide) before and after physical activity can help prevent friction and sweating from exacerbating the condition. Parents should also be advised about appropriate footwear choices, including breathable materials (non-synthetic), wearing two cotton or woollen socks, and changing socks regularly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antifungal cream\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for tinea pedis, but the absence of scaling, particularly in the toe webs, and the characteristic smooth, shiny appearance make fungal infection unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical corticosteroid cream\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as first-line treatment for JPD as the condition is primarily related to friction and excessive moisture rather than inflammation. Prolonged use of topical steroids may thin the skin and worsen the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antihistamines\u003C/strong\u003E would not be helpful as JPD is not an allergic condition and pruritus is not typically a major feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWet dressings\u003C/strong\u003E would be counterproductive as excess moisture is part of the problem in JPD. The goal is to keep the feet dry and protected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe natural history of JPD is that it typically improves with age and resolves by adolescence. Management focuses on prevention and symptom control rather than cure. Parents should be reassured about the benign nature of the condition while emphasising the importance of regular preventive measures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Juvenile plantar dermatosis is characterised by smooth, shiny, red skin on the forefoot with painful fissuring.","Management focuses on prevention with emollients and barrier creams rather than treating inflammation.","The condition typically improves with age and resolves by adolescence."],"references":["Oakley A, Eshraghi A. Juvenile plantar dermatosis. DermNet NZ. 2020.  Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/juvenile-plantar-dermatosis","Kalia S, Adams SP. Dermacase. Juvenile plantar dermatosis. Can Fam Physician. 2005.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC1479460/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86850"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18523"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86850"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T13:00:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T13:00:36+09:30"},"relationship